Desert Ecology

For this assignment, we are going to use a modified data set on desert ecology. The data are from: S. K. Morgan Ernest, Thomas J. Valone, and James H. Brown. 2009. Long-term monitoring and experimental manipulation of a Chihuahuan Desert ecosystem near Portal, Arizona, USA. Ecology 90:1708.

  1. How many genera and species are represented in the data? What are the total number of observations? Which species is most/ least frequently sampled in the study?

There are 26 genera and 40 species represented in the data. There were a total of 34786 observations. Merriami is the most frequently sampled while clarki, scutalatus, tereticaudus, tigris, uniparens,and viridis were the least frequently sampled.

  1. What is the proportion of taxa included in this study? Show a table and plot that reflects this count.
deserts %>%
  count(taxa)
## # A tibble: 4 x 2
##   taxa        n
## * <chr>   <int>
## 1 Bird      450
## 2 Rabbit     75
## 3 Reptile    14
## 4 Rodent  34247
deserts %>% 
  filter(taxa != "NA") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = taxa))+
  geom_bar()+
  scale_y_log10()+
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title = "Taxa of the Chihuahan Desert", x = "Taxa", y = "Count")

  1. For the taxa included in the study, use the fill option to show the proportion of individuals sampled by plot_type.
deserts %>% 
  filter(taxa != "NA") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = taxa, fill = plot_type))+
  geom_bar()+
  scale_y_log10()+
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title = "Plot Type Proportions Among Chihuahuan Desert Taxa", x = "Taxa", y = "Count")

  1. What is the range of weight for each species included in the study? Remove any observations of weight that are NA so they do not show up in the plot.
deserts %>% 
  filter(weight != "NA") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(species, weight), y = weight, color = species)) +
  geom_boxplot()+
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title = "Weight Range of Species in the Chihuahuan Desert", x = "Species",  y = "Weight")

  1. Add another layer to your answer from #4 using geom_point to get an idea of how many measurements were taken for each species.
deserts %>% 
  filter(weight != "NA") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(species, weight), y = weight, color = species)) +
  geom_boxplot()+
  scale_y_log10()+
  geom_point(size = 0.5)+
  coord_flip()+
  labs(title = "Weight Range of Species in the Chihuahuan Desert", x = "Species",  y = "Weight (log10)")

  1. What is the relationship between weight and hindfoot length? Consider whether or not over plotting is an issue.

The data is very scattered, therefore it is difficult to make any assumptions about their relationship, but it appears to be a positive one. It seems that over plotting is an issue with this data.

deserts %>% 
  filter(weight != "NA") %>% 
  filter(hindfoot_length != "NA") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = weight, y = hindfoot_length))+
  geom_jitter(size = 0.25, na.rm = T)+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")+
  labs(title = "Relationship Between Species Weight and Hindfoot Length", x = "Weight", y = "Hindfoot Length")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

  1. Which two species have, on average, the highest weight? Once you have identified them, make a new column that is a ratio of weight to hindfoot_length. Make a plot that shows the range of this new ratio and fill by sex.

Albigula and spectabilis have the highest average weight.

deserts %>% 
  group_by(species) %>% 
  filter(weight != "NA") %>% 
  summarise(avg_weight = mean(weight)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(avg_weight))
## # A tibble: 22 x 2
##    species      avg_weight
##    <chr>             <dbl>
##  1 albigula          159. 
##  2 spectabilis       120. 
##  3 spilosoma          93.5
##  4 hispidus           65.6
##  5 fulviventer        58.9
##  6 ochrognathus       55.4
##  7 ordii              48.9
##  8 merriami           43.2
##  9 baileyi            31.7
## 10 leucogaster        31.6
## #  with 12 more rows
deserts %>% 
  filter(weight != "NA") %>% 
  filter(hindfoot_length != "NA") %>% 
  filter(sex != "NA") %>%
  filter(species == "albigula" | species == "spectabilis") %>% 
  group_by(species) %>% 
  mutate(wl_ratio = weight/hindfoot_length) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = species, y = wl_ratio, fill = sex))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  labs(title = "Weight-Hindfoot Length Ratio Comparison of Albigula and Spectabilis", x = "Species", y = "Weight : Hindfoot Length Ratio")

  1. Make one plot of your choice! Make sure to include at least two of the aesthetics options you have learned. look at the number of observations
deserts %>% 
  filter(species == "penicillatus") %>% 
  filter(sex != "NA") %>% 
  group_by(year, sex) %>% 
  summarise(obs_count = n(), .groups = "keep") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = obs_count, fill = sex))+
  geom_col()+
  labs(title = "Penicillatus Observation Count by Sex (1977-2002)", x = "Year", y = "Number of Observations")
